Welcome to October's Turing-Roche newsletter! Here you can find what's new in the Turing-Roche strategic partnership and opportunities, events and news from both The Alan Turing Institute, Roche and beyond.

Our [five year partnership](https://eur01.safelinks.protection.outlook.com/?url=http%3A%2F%2Felink.turing.ac.uk%2Fc%2F7%%2FQxcw6_hEaoiyZgQ7mjthjQ&data=05%7C01%7Cvhellon%40turing.ac.uk%7C4c6229120aea4a6c0e0808dbcbc7fbd4%7C4395f4a7e4554f958a9f1fbaef6384f9%7C0%7C0%7C638327832045098024%7CUnknown%7CTWFpbGZsb3d8eyJWIjoiMC4wLjAwMDAiLCJQIjoiV2luMzIiLCJBTiI6Ik1haWwiLCJXVCI6Mn0%3D%7C3000%7C%7C%7C&sdata=XO45aq15tXC1cWaUXEdTuq1LPy6nd%2BjW0%2BEdUWbHHuc%3D&reserved=0) was set up officially in June 2021 following a successful [Data Study Group](https://eur01.safelinks.protection.outlook.com/?url=http%3A%2F%2Felink.turing.ac.uk%2Fc%2F7%%2F8EKalXn4w_aBpUS6jnMwSQ&data=05%7C01%7Cvhellon%40turing.ac.uk%7C4c6229120aea4a6c0e0808dbcbc7fbd4%7C4395f4a7e4554f958a9f1fbaef6384f9%7C0%7C0%7C638327832045098024%7CUnknown%7CTWFpbGZsb3d8eyJWIjoiMC4wLjAwMDAiLCJQIjoiV2luMzIiLCJBTiI6Ik1haWwiLCJXVCI6Mn0%3D%7C3000%7C%7C%7C&sdata=Zw53mrlvk1NtL%2BEJtV32wZmtdD3RqWFGZUibDBPZPS4%3D&reserved=0) and a 12 week research project on lung cancer treatment. Our 'North Star' is **to enable the generation of insights to better understand patient and disease heterogeneity and its relevance to clinical outcomes at an unprecedented level of precision in order to improve clinical care.**

We will be covering multiple activities over the five years to work towards our North Star, as well as building strong connections and collaborations between the Alan Turing Institute, Roche and the wider community.

If you have anything you'd like featured in a future newsletter then please get in touch with Vicky Hellon, Community Manager for the partnership at <vhellon@turing.ac.uk>

If you would like to share this newsletter with relevant colleagues please direct them to sign-up [here](https://eur01.safelinks.protection.outlook.com/?url=http%3A%2F%2Felink.turing.ac.uk%2Fc%2F7%%2FJXF0AqnEYWoegTbE5TaETQ&data=05%7C01%7Cvhellon%40turing.ac.uk%7C4c6229120aea4a6c0e0808dbcbc7fbd4%7C4395f4a7e4554f958a9f1fbaef6384f9%7C0%7C0%7C638327832045098024%7CUnknown%7CTWFpbGZsb3d8eyJWIjoiMC4wLjAwMDAiLCJQIjoiV2luMzIiLCJBTiI6Ik1haWwiLCJXVCI6Mn0%3D%7C3000%7C%7C%7C&sdata=KnMrcr3mc%2BhRpUE8svM1s%2FXJvz%2FvmBoye3fmHRrMIXY%3D&reserved=0).

### New Partnership Publication on Predictive Uncertainty in Clinical AI tools published in Nature Medicine

Our partnership team members Chris Banerji, Rohan Chakraborty, Chris Harbron and Ben MacArthur have written an article on predictive uncertainty in clinical AI tools. [Published in Nature Medicine](https://eur01.safelinks.protection.outlook.com/?url=http%3A%2F%2Felink.turing.ac.uk%2Fc%2F7%%2FwVI1QasdAPD8Qwl83PjEww&data=05%7C01%7Cvhellon%40turing.ac.uk%7C4c6229120aea4a6c0e0808dbcbc7fbd4%7C4395f4a7e4554f958a9f1fbaef6384f9%7C0%7C0%7C638327832045254286%7CUnknown%7CTWFpbGZsb3d8eyJWIjoiMC4wLjAwMDAiLCJQIjoiV2luMzIiLCJBTiI6Ik1haWwiLCJXVCI6Mn0%3D%7C3000%7C%7C%7C&sdata=VNQyqCcbfrxcYtP%2FaImDd4QnwWg9xsVoV%2Bly8dcHSSQ%3D&reserved=0), they discuss that whilst AI tools usually aim to maximise predictive accuracy, personalised measures of uncertainty, using new techniques such as conformal prediction, are needed for clinical AI to realize its potential and improve human health. The team are now planning further research to build on this comments paper, so keep your eyes peeled! 

### Knowledge Share Series Event: Digital Twins in Health

**24 October 2023**

Join us for our [partnership knowledge share series](https://eur01.safelinks.protection.outlook.com/?url=http%3A%2F%2Felink.turing.ac.uk%2Fc%2F7%%2FbOQqKGWehp2AJaD46n8tyw&data=05%7C01%7Cvhellon%40turing.ac.uk%7C4c6229120aea4a6c0e0808dbcbc7fbd4%7C4395f4a7e4554f958a9f1fbaef6384f9%7C0%7C0%7C638327832045254286%7CUnknown%7CTWFpbGZsb3d8eyJWIjoiMC4wLjAwMDAiLCJQIjoiV2luMzIiLCJBTiI6Ik1haWwiLCJXVCI6Mn0%3D%7C3000%7C%7C%7C&sdata=3vnmqtr9ZTauMEapCP%2F1fpbvp3HuEq7yGCOvjTahGxU%3D&reserved=0). Our aim is to bring together members of the Turing and Roche networks and the wider scientific community to share different academic and industry perspectives on areas related to patient/treatment heterogeneity and data science more generally.

October's event is on the 24th and this month our theme will be Digital Twins in health. There has been recent interest in how digital twins can be developed to investigate disease states, predict patient response to treatment and ultimately improve health and wellbeing.

We will be hearing from Steven Niederer, Professor of Biomedical Engineering at King's College London and co-director of the TRIC-DT: a Turing Institute Research and Innovation Cluster (TRIC) focusing on digital twins (DT) and Jon Walsh, co-founder and the Head of Modeling at Unlearn.AI. You can register for the event [here](https://eur01.safelinks.protection.outlook.com/?url=http%3A%2F%2Felink.turing.ac.uk%2Fc%2F7%%2FhKCqi8F26guPz5i0oNU_XA&data=05%7C01%7Cvhellon%40turing.ac.uk%7C4c6229120aea4a6c0e0808dbcbc7fbd4%7C4395f4a7e4554f958a9f1fbaef6384f9%7C0%7C0%7C638327832045254286%7CUnknown%7CTWFpbGZsb3d8eyJWIjoiMC4wLjAwMDAiLCJQIjoiV2luMzIiLCJBTiI6Ik1haWwiLCJXVCI6Mn0%3D%7C3000%7C%7C%7C&sdata=W7UZ6HgRgDZv0hInbZNauC%2FFUN1qSpS%2BT9C0GesJdac%3D&reserved=0).

### Turing Online Learning Course: AI Fairness on Social Media

The Turing online learning platform has a new free course covering the fundamentals of algorithmic fairness, the most common biases in machine learning, and the importance of ethical and legal principles in AI design, training, and deployment. The course discusses recent examples of algorithmic fairness in social media, AI fairness tools to mitigate discrimination and bias in ML models, and various methods and studies that address social biases in graph datasets and NLP methods.

The goal of the course is to educate and prepare data scientists and engineers to ensure that their AI models are ethical, fair, and safe for use in human-in-the-loop applications. Find out more [here](https://eur01.safelinks.protection.outlook.com/?url=http%3A%2F%2Felink.turing.ac.uk%2Fc%2F7%_X2NsZGVlPXNQVVN6c3ZCbU1RY0pkR2NFMldET3VEQzdHam9NX2dSd1lqUGZqZTlYSDJDcEZDWXE0RHhsWWwzMkJDRkU5SUgmcmVjaXBpZW50aWQ9Y29udGFjdC00ODgwYThjMzkyM2NlYzExOGM2MjAwMjI0ODQzNGZlYi1mOGNkMWIyM2UzM2E0MWRlYmQ2OGJhMTU5ODAzZDJlNiZlc2lkPTQ3ZmQ0M2QxLTJiNjgtZWUxMS05YWU3LTYwNDViZDBlNmJjZiJ9%2Fc61Vb2UM71Q_DaQwToPJ1A&data=05%7C01%7Cvhellon%40turing.ac.uk%7C4c6229120aea4a6c0e0808dbcbc7fbd4%7C4395f4a7e4554f958a9f1fbaef6384f9%7C0%7C0%7C638327832045254286%7CUnknown%7CTWFpbGZsb3d8eyJWIjoiMC4wLjAwMDAiLCJQIjoiV2luMzIiLCJBTiI6Ik1haWwiLCJXVCI6Mn0%3D%7C3000%7C%7C%7C&sdata=Bza7u%2BO2%2B%2F7ijQhZVrGhvCFCfrkt%2FCd54mw7vhCFvWE%3D&reserved=0).

### Turing Causal Inference Interest Group Seminar Event: DagSim

**06 November 2023**

The Turing Institute's [Causal Inference Group ](https://eur01.safelinks.protection.outlook.com/?url=http%3A%2F%2Felink.turing.ac.uk%2Fc%2F7%%2Fa6rGxuIXZKpAq-o0k4hrCA&data=05%7C01%7Cvhellon%40turing.ac.uk%7C4c6229120aea4a6c0e0808dbcbc7fbd4%7C4395f4a7e4554f958a9f1fbaef6384f9%7C0%7C0%7C638327832045410592%7CUnknown%7CTWFpbGZsb3d8eyJWIjoiMC4wLjAwMDAiLCJQIjoiV2luMzIiLCJBTiI6Ik1haWwiLCJXVCI6Mn0%3D%7C3000%7C%7C%7C&sdata=CUuzown9ZEotlXI6afbUvheMp4aHCzn9QlMSOT2JDR8%3D&reserved=0)are resuming their monthly seminars. ### UCL Symposium on Statistical Methods for Health Equity

**08 November 2023**

## Featured Community Scholar of the Month
As you may have seen, we have welcomed our first cohort of Turing-Roche Community Scholars: 10 UK PhD students who are joining the partnership for 12 months to develop community-based projects for the partnership, alongside their ongoing PhD studies. Each month we are featuring a different scholar in our newsletter.

You can find out more about our community scholars [here](https://eur01.safelinks.protection.outlook.com/?url=http%3A%2F%2Felink.turing.ac.uk%2Fc%2F7%%2F5e1KbRQlYgk58zazqwdVyw&data=05%7C01%7Cvhellon%40turing.ac.uk%7C4c6229120aea4a6c0e0808dbcbc7fbd4%7C4395f4a7e4554f958a9f1fbaef6384f9%7C0%7C0%7C638327832045566851%7CUnknown%7CTWFpbGZsb3d8eyJWIjoiMC4wLjAwMDAiLCJQIjoiV2luMzIiLCJBTiI6Ik1haWwiLCJXVCI6Mn0%3D%7C3000%7C%7C%7C&sdata=ODbuTn%2FY8NTZurzxS%2FPXcZYftd3VPFblwxQVtePcS8w%3D&reserved=0) and their plans for their projects [here](https://eur01.safelinks.protection.outlook.com/?url=http%3A%2F%2Felink.turing.ac.uk%2Fc%2F7%%2Fwdx4CmZmR8pyQRvcsn_r0g&data=05%7C01%7Cvhellon%40turing.ac.uk%7C4c6229120aea4a6c0e0808dbcbc7fbd4%7C4395f4a7e4554f958a9f1fbaef6384f9%7C0%7C0%7C638327832045723113%7CUnknown%7CTWFpbGZsb3d8eyJWIjoiMC4wLjAwMDAiLCJQIjoiV2luMzIiLCJBTiI6Ik1haWwiLCJXVCI6Mn0%3D%7C3000%7C%7C%7C&sdata=7O8m%2FLtchTIGq8pzwqUzBYnd%2BzZpBycdACUV%2FyCm%2BZU%3D&reserved=0).

This month's scholar is Sarah Buehler, from University College London.

![](https://file-eu.clickdimensions.com/turingacuk-ap7zg/files/sarah_buehler.jpg)

**Tell us a little bit about yourself and your current research:**

My research lies at the intersection of neuroscience, psychiatry and pharmacology. I am interested in the cross-diagnostic mechanisms underlying symptoms of anxiety and depression, which are very common and debilitating psychiatric disorders that are also highly heterogenous and comorbid. To better capture the heterogeneity of these patient populations, I investigate cognitive constructs such as affective processing, memory and mood and how they relate to differences in depression and anxiety symptomatology. In the hopes of improving future clinical care, the focus of my research is on better understanding how the most prescribed commonly pharmacological treatments, i.e., antidepressants, work differently (or not at all) for different people by affecting these cognitive processes. With an improved understanding of antidepressant response and the heterogeneity of outcomes I am hoping that treatments can be better targeted to those who are most likely to respond to them.

**What is your planned community scholar project? Why is this of interest to you?**

My community scholar project is a translational science methods club that brings together members of Turing, Roche as well as the wider academic but also clinical community to focus on how we can translate from data to science to clinic. This should foster discussion on how to deal with data, inference and the populations we study, addressing questions such as how to deal with different types of data, what inferences can be made from the methods we use and how this can capture and benefit patient populations. Ultimately my hope is to bring together researchers from academia and industry as well as perspectives from the clinic to critically evaluate and hopefully improve the way health data science can be conducted, generalized, and implemented.

**What is your favourite meal- breakfast, lunch or dinner?**

Breakfast - it is the most important meal of the day and my reason to get out of bed in the morning (it is also the only socially acceptable meal that can consist entirely of chocolate).

## Publication of the Month
![](https://file-eu.clickdimensions.com/turingacuk-ap7zg/files/patrick-tomasso-oaqk7qqnh_c-unsplash2.jpg)

**Expectation cues and false percepts generate stimulus-specific activity in distinct layers of the early visual cortex Laminar profile of visual false percepts**

In addition to our new partnership publication above, our featured Community Scholar Sarah has chosen [this paper](https://eur01.safelinks.protection.outlook.com/?url=http%3A%2F%2Felink.turing.ac.uk%2Fc%2F7%%2FxrTpUN_K_zGcC4Ko17zAvg&data=05%7C01%7Cvhellon%40turing.ac.uk%7C4c6229120aea4a6c0e0808dbcbc7fbd4%7C4395f4a7e4554f958a9f1fbaef6384f9%7C0%7C0%7C638327832045723113%7CUnknown%7CTWFpbGZsb3d8eyJWIjoiMC4wLjAwMDAiLCJQIjoiV2luMzIiLCJBTiI6Ik1haWwiLCJXVCI6Mn0%3D%7C3000%7C%7C%7C&sdata=g9TbIeTUFhUCP8R57KnK%2FZqAmGvnIrpyQ7lJBEJmSc8%3D&reserved=0) for our October publication of the month. It was published in the Journal of Neuroscience and led by researchers from University College London. 'This paper is quite exciting because it shows how our brain's response to the world is guided by our expectations and that even in the general population it is common to perceive things that are not actually there (false percepts). This will hopefully inspire future work to improve our understanding the brain's perceptual mechanisms, our subjective human experience and clinical populations such as those suffering from psychosis.'
